We based the decision to use ruggedized laptops on the following criteria:


ruggedized units allowed for use under difficult field conditions, typical of the developing world;



specially designed screens allowed for viewing in direct sunlight (common at the time of day and setting of most interviews);



internal GPS units and GIS programming provided interview teams with maps and real-time navigation of the survey region;



laptops were relatively light, weighing 5.1 lb and equipped with a 10.4" screen to view a full-sized survey form;



the touch screens allowed for rapid recordings of responses many of which were coded as drop-down menus, radio buttons, and check boxes; and



rechargeable and back-up batteries provided for a full day of work. Approximately 8–10 hours of use was possible with the two batteries.

Although we cannot test for differences in survey time for the PAPI (administered in 2005) and CAPI surveys (administered in 2009) because of changes in the survey length and design, we are able to compare changes in survey time by week to investigate learning effects as well as compare variability in survey time by interviewer to infer mode effects. The survey increased in size by 63%, from 619 questions to 1,009 from 2005 to 2009, although this was not accompanied by an equal increase in the time needed to complete the survey (see Table 2
). This suggests that the use of CAPI may have reduced survey time. We expected that the CAPI survey would exhibit a greater reduction in survey time between weeks 1 and 2 as enumerators learned and adapted to the new technology. However, the similar rate of change exhibited between CAPI and PAPI survey waves suggests that the training period and methods utilized in 2009 adequately familiarized enumerators with the technology thereby equalizing learning curve effects (Figure 2
). Finally, variation in survey time is significantly greater for the CAPI survey, but the variances for the two surveyors involved on both years exhibit no significant differences. In sum, we find few, if any, significant mode effects attributable to the move from PAPI to CAPI for this panel. This is likely because of the data checking methods and oversight utilized throughout the PAPI and CAPI field campaigns. In both cases, data were checked on a daily basis, surveyors were accompanied by management members as often as possible, and questions were raised and answered at regular meetings attended by the managing staff and enumerators.
